-- Market Chatter- Corporate finance press digest
-- 
-- Mon Oct 06, 2014 12:23AM EDT
-- None



Oct 6 (Reuters) - The following corporate finance-related stories were reported by media:

* The National Basketball Association has reached long-term media rights contracts with Walt Disney Co <DIS.N> and Time Warner Inc's <TWX.N> Turner Broadcasting, more than doubling the fees it received under the previous contracts, the Wall Street Journal reported, citing people familiar with the matter. [ID:nL3N0S10KA]  * A group of 12 banks, including BNP Paribas SA <BNPP.PA>, Credit Suisse Group AG <CSGN.VX>, Goldman Sachs Group Inc <GS.N>, HSBC Holdings <HSBA.L>, and JP Morgan Chase & Co <JPM.N> are working together to set up a one-stop bond shop for buyers and sellers of corporate bonds, the Wall Street Journal reported, citing people familiar with the matter. [ID:nL3N0S10TK]  * Silicon Valley stalwart Hewlett-Packard Co <HPQ.N>, which has struggled to adapt to the new era of mobile and online computing, plans to split into two companies as it looks to put more focus on the faster-growing corporate services market, according to a Wall Street Journal report on Sunday. [ID:nL2N0S00P4]  * Commodities trader Mercuria is considering a strategic review of Henry Bath, a metals warehousing, storage and handling business, which it had bought from JPMorgan Chase & Co <JPM.N>, the Financial times reported. [ID:nL2N0S015Y]  For the deals of the day click on [DEALS/]